---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="What Is a Healthy BMI? Complete Adult Guide"
  description="What counts as a healthy BMI for adults? Learn the WHO ranges for men and women, what your BMI number means for health risk, and the limitations of BMI as a health measure."
>
  <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl px-4 py-12 sm:px-6">

    <p class="text-sm font-medium uppercase tracking-wider text-(--color-accent-deep)">Guide</p>
    <h1 class="font-display mt-2 text-4xl font-bold text-(--color-ink)">
      What Is a Healthy BMI? A Complete Guide for Adults
    </h1>
    <p class="mt-4 text-lg text-(--color-body)">
      BMI is one of the most searched health numbers — but what does it actually mean, and when does it matter?
    </p>

    <div class="mt-4 text-xs text-(--color-mute)">Published: June 2026 · 6 min read</div>

    <div class="mt-10 space-y-8 text-(--color-body) leading-relaxed">

      <section>
        <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-semibold text-(--color-ink)">The short answer</h2>
        <p class="mt-3">
          The World Health Organization (WHO) defines a healthy BMI range as <strong>18.5 to 24.9 kg/m²</strong>
          for adults of all sexes and most ethnicities. Below 18.5 is underweight; 25–29.9 is overweight;
          30 or above is obese.
        </p>
        <div class="mt-5 overflow-x-auto rounded-xl border border-(--color-hairline)">
          <table class="w-full text-left text-sm">
            <thead class="bg-(--color-canvas)">
              <tr>
                <th class="px-4 py-3 font-semibold text-(--color-ink)">Category</th>
                <th class="px-4 py-3 font-semibold text-(--color-ink)">BMI Range</th>
                <th class="px-4 py-3 font-semibold text-(--color-ink)">Health Signal</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody class="divide-y divide-(--color-hairline)">
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-3">Severe thinness</td><td class="px-4 py-3">&lt; 16</td><td class="px-4 py-3">Critical — seek medical care</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-3">Underweight</td><td class="px-4 py-3">16 – 18.4</td><td class="px-4 py-3">Increased risk of malnutrition</td></tr>
              <tr class="bg-(--color-normal)/8"><td class="px-4 py-3 font-medium">Normal weight</td><td class="px-4 py-3">18.5 – 24.9</td><td class="px-4 py-3">✅ Lowest population-level risk</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-3">Overweight</td><td class="px-4 py-3">25 – 29.9</td><td class="px-4 py-3">Elevated risk for some conditions</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-3">Obese Class I</td><td class="px-4 py-3">30 – 34.9</td><td class="px-4 py-3">High risk — medical evaluation advised</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-3">Obese Class II</td><td class="px-4 py-3">35 – 39.9</td><td class="px-4 py-3">Very high risk</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="px-4 py-3">Obese Class III</td><td class="px-4 py-3">≥ 40</td><td class="px-4 py-3">Severe risk — bariatric options may apply</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-semibold text-(--color-ink)">How BMI is calculated</h2>
        <p class="mt-3">
          BMI = weight (kg) ÷ height² (m²). For example, a person weighing 70 kg at 175 cm:
          70 ÷ (1.75 × 1.75) = 70 ÷ 3.0625 ≈ <strong>22.9</strong>.
        </p>
        <p class="mt-3">
          In imperial units: BMI = 703 × weight (lb) ÷ height² (in²).
          Use our <a href="/" class="text-(--color-link) hover:underline">free calculator</a> to get
          your number instantly without doing the maths.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-semibold text-(--color-ink)">Healthy BMI for men vs women</h2>
        <p class="mt-3">
          The formula and thresholds are identical for men and women. However, at the same BMI, women
          typically carry 6–11% more body fat than men, due to hormones and reproductive physiology.
          A BMI of 24 in a woman may represent more body fat than the same number in a man — yet both
          fall comfortably in the "normal" range.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-semibold text-(--color-ink)">Healthy BMI by age</h2>
        <p class="mt-3">
          The WHO thresholds are the same across all adult ages. However, research suggests that slightly
          higher BMI values may be less harmful in older adults (65+), where low BMI is more closely
          associated with frailty, malnutrition, and mortality. Some clinicians use a target range of
          22–27 for older adults rather than the strict 18.5–24.9.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-semibold text-(--color-ink)">When "normal" BMI isn't healthy</h2>
        <p class="mt-3">
          Normal-weight obesity (NWO) occurs when a person has a BMI under 25 but carries excess body
          fat, particularly in the abdomen. Studies suggest 20–30% of people in the "normal" BMI category
          have metabolic risk factors including high blood pressure, insulin resistance, and elevated
          triglycerides.
        </p>
        <p class="mt-3">
          The opposite is also true — "metabolically healthy obesity" describes individuals with BMI
          above 30 who have normal blood markers. Fitness level, diet quality, and genetics all mediate
          health risk independently of BMI.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-semibold text-(--color-ink)">What to do with your result</h2>
        <ul class="mt-3 list-disc pl-5 space-y-2">
          <li>Use BMI as a starting point, not a diagnosis</li>
          <li>Pair with waist circumference (men: &lt;94 cm / women: &lt;80 cm for lower risk)</li>
          <li>Get blood work if your BMI is outside the healthy range</li>
          <li>Focus on sustainable habits — consistent diet, regular movement, adequate sleep</li>
          <li>If concerned, consult a GP, dietitian, or certified health professional</li>
        </ul>
      </section>

    </div>

    <div class="mt-12 rounded-xl border border-(--color-hairline) bg-(--color-canvas) p-5">
      <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-(--color-ink)">Calculate your BMI now</p>
      <p class="mt-1 text-sm text-(--color-body)">Instant result in metric or US units — no sign-up needed.</p>
      <a href="/" class="mt-3 inline-block rounded-xl bg-(--color-accent) px-5 py-2.5 text-sm font-semibold text-white hover:opacity-90 transition">
        Open BMI Calculator →
      </a>
    </div>

    <p class="mt-8 text-xs text-(--color-mute)">
      This article is for educational purposes only and is not a substitute for professional medical advice.
    </p>
    <p class="mt-4 text-sm">
      <a href="/blog" class="text-(--color-link) hover:underline">← All articles</a>
    </p>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
